22:08.720 --> 22:14.400
something that stops bacteria from becoming more complex, because they didn't. That's a fact that

22:14.400 --> 22:19.920
they emerged four billion years ago, and something happened two billion years ago, but the bacteria

22:20.000 --> 22:26.000
themselves didn't change. They remain bacterial. So there is no trajectory, necessary trajectory

22:26.000 --> 22:30.400
towards great complexity in human beings at the end of it. It's very easy to imagine that without

22:30.400 --> 22:34.880
photosynthesis arising, or without eukaryotes arising, that a planet could be full of bacteria

22:34.880 --> 22:39.840
and nothing else. We'll get to that, because that's a brilliant invention. And there's a few

22:39.840 --> 22:46.240
brilliant invention along the way. But what is life? If you were to show up on Earth, but to

22:46.320 --> 22:51.440
take that time machine, and you said, asking yourself the question, is this a stepping stone

22:51.440 --> 22:58.160
towards life? As you step along, when you see the early bacteria, how would you know it's life?

23:00.320 --> 23:03.920
This is really important question when you go to other planets and look for life.

23:06.320 --> 23:11.520
What is the framework of telling a difference between a rock and a bacteria?

23:12.160 --> 23:16.480
I mean, the question's kind of both impossible to answer and trivial at the same time,

23:16.480 --> 23:20.560
and I don't like to answer it, because I don't think there is an answer. I think we're trying to

23:20.560 --> 23:27.760
describe the process at the same time. There's lots of at least 40 or 50 different definitions

23:27.760 --> 23:33.760
of life out there, and most of them are obviously bad in one way or another.

23:34.320 --> 23:40.800
I mean, there's freaks. I can never remember the exact words that people use, but there's a NASA

23:41.680 --> 23:48.400
working definition of life, which more or less says a system which is capable of a

23:48.400 --> 23:51.680
self-sustaining system capable of evolution or something along those lines.

23:52.560 --> 23:57.600
And I immediately have a problem with the words self-sustaining, because it's sustained by the

23:57.600 --> 24:02.400
environment. And I know what they're getting at. I know what they're trying to say, but I pick a

24:02.400 --> 24:07.360
hole in that. And there's always wags who say, but by that definition, a rabbit is not alive.

24:07.360 --> 24:12.160
Only a pair of rabbits would be alive, because a single rabbit is incapable of copying itself.

24:12.720 --> 24:19.040
There are all kinds of pedantic, silly, but also important, objections to any hypothesis.

24:19.040 --> 24:25.200
The real question is what is... We can argue all day, or people do argue all day about,

24:25.200 --> 24:30.880
is a virus alive or not? And it depends on the content. But most biologists could not agree

24:30.880 --> 24:34.160
about that. So then what about a jumping gene, a retro element or something like that? It's even

24:34.160 --> 24:41.520
simpler than a virus, but it's capable of converting its environment into a copy of itself.

24:42.960 --> 24:46.880
And that's about as close... This is not a definition, but this is a kind of a description of life,

24:47.440 --> 24:54.160
is that it's able to parasitize the environment, and that goes for plants as well as animals and

24:54.160 --> 25:02.320
bacteria and viruses to make a relatively exact copy of themselves, information on the

25:02.320 --> 25:08.000
exact copy of themselves. By the way, it doesn't really have to be a copy of itself, right? It just

25:08.000 --> 25:17.200
has to be... You have to create something that's interesting. The way evolution is... So it is

25:17.200 --> 25:23.280
extremely powerful process of evolution, which is basically make a copy yourself and sometimes mess

25:23.280 --> 25:27.680
up a little bit. Okay, that seems to work really well. I wonder if it's possible to

25:28.400 --> 25:33.760
mess up big time as a standard, as the default. It's called a hopeful monster. And

25:35.840 --> 25:41.840
in principle, it can. Actually, it turns out, I would say that this is due a reemergence. This

25:41.840 --> 25:45.440
is some amazing work from Michael Levin. I don't know if you came across him, but

25:46.240 --> 25:52.800
if you haven't interviewed him, you should interview him. Yeah, yeah, I'm talking to him in

25:52.800 --> 26:00.160
a few days. Oh, fantastic. So I mentioned there's two people that, if I may mention,

26:00.880 --> 26:06.560
Andre Capati is a friend who's really admired in the AI community, said you absolutely must talk

26:07.200 --> 26:13.520
to Michael and to Nick. So this, of course, I'm a huge fan of yours, so I'm really fortunate

26:13.520 --> 26:18.640
that we can actually make this happen. Anyway, your second. Well, Michael Levin is doing amazing work

26:19.280 --> 26:23.200
basically about the way in which electrical fields control development.

26:24.720 --> 26:29.120
And he's done some work with planarian worms, so flatworms, where he'll tell you all about

26:29.120 --> 26:32.640
this. So I won't say any more than the minimum, but basically you can cut their head off and they'll

26:32.640 --> 26:38.880
redevelop a different, a new head. But the head that they develop depends if you knock out just one

26:41.280 --> 26:45.200
iron pump in a membrane, so you change the electrical circuitry just a little bit,

26:45.280 --> 26:50.080
you can come up with a completely different head. It can be a head which is similar to those that

26:50.080 --> 26:54.640
diverged 150 million years ago, or it can be a head which no one's ever seen before, a different

26:54.640 --> 27:00.880
kind of head. Now, that is really, you might say a hopeful monster. This is a kind of leap into a

27:00.880 --> 27:06.160
different direction. The only question for natural selection is, does it work? Is the change itself

27:06.720 --> 27:10.960
feasible as a single change? And the answer is yes, it's just a small change to a single gene.

27:11.040 --> 27:14.800
And the second thing is it gives rise to a completely different morphology.

27:14.800 --> 27:23.440
Does it work? And if it works, that can easily be a shift. But for it to be a speciation, for it to

27:24.400 --> 27:31.920
continue, for it to give rise to a different morphology over time, then it has to be perpetuated.

27:31.920 --> 27:40.400
So that shift, that change in that one gene has to work well enough that it is selected and it

27:40.400 --> 27:45.680
goes on. And copied enough times to where you can really test it. So the likelihood it would be

27:45.680 --> 27:50.320
lost, but there will be some occasions where it survives. And yes, the idea that we can have

27:50.320 --> 27:56.560
sudden fairly abrupt changes in evolution I think is time for a rebirth. What about this idea that

27:57.520 --> 28:05.040
kind of trying to mathematicalize a definition of life and saying how many steps, the shortest

28:05.040 --> 28:08.880
amount of steps it takes to build the thing, almost like an engineering view of it?

28:10.160 --> 28:16.160
I like that view, because I think that in a sense that's not very far away from what a

28:16.160 --> 28:20.400
hypothesis needs to do to be a testable hypothesis for the origin of life. You need to spell out,

28:20.400 --> 28:26.480
here's each step, and here's the experiment to do for each step. The idea that we can do it in the

28:26.480 --> 28:31.680
lab, some people say, well, we'll have created life within five years, but ask them what they

28:31.680 --> 28:38.880
mean by life. We have a planet four billion years ago with these vent systems across the entire

28:38.880 --> 28:42.720
surface of the planet, and we have millions of years if we wanted. I have a feeling that we're

28:42.720 --> 28:47.920
not talking about millions of years. I have a feeling we're talking about maybe millions of

28:47.920 --> 28:52.080
nanoseconds or picoseconds. We're talking about chemistry, which is happening quickly.

28:53.840 --> 29:00.960
But we still need to constrain those steps, but we've got a planet doing similar chemistry. You

29:00.960 --> 29:06.480
asked about a trajectory. The trajectory is the planetary trajectory. The planet has properties.

29:06.480 --> 29:09.920
See, it's basically got a lot of iron at the center of it. It's got a lot of electrons at the

29:09.920 --> 29:14.640
center of it. It's more oxidized on the outside, partly because of the sun, and partly because

29:14.640 --> 29:20.480
the heat of volcanoes puts out oxidized gases. The planet is a battery, it's a giant battery.

29:22.080 --> 29:26.480
We have a flow of electrons going from inside to outside in these hydrothermal vents, and that's

29:26.480 --> 29:32.560
the same topology that a cell has. A cell is basically just a microversion of the planet.

29:35.360 --> 29:39.840
There is a trajectory in all of that, and there's an inevitability that certain types of chemical

29:39.840 --> 29:46.160
reaction are going to be favored over others. There's an inevitability in what happens in water,

29:46.160 --> 29:51.840
the chemistry that happens in water. Some will be immiscible with water and will form membranes and

29:51.840 --> 30:00.080
will form insoluble structures. Nobody really understands water very well. It's another big

30:00.080 --> 30:05.600
question for experiments on the origin of life. What do you put it in? What kind of structure do

30:05.600 --> 30:10.880
we want to induce in this water? Because the last thing it's likely to be is just bulk water.

30:11.760 --> 30:14.240
How fundamental is water to life, would you say?

30:14.240 --> 30:20.960
I would say pretty fundamental. I wouldn't like to say it's impossible for life to start any other

30:20.960 --> 30:30.160
way, but water is everywhere. Water is extremely good at what it does, and carbon works in water

30:30.160 --> 30:35.600
especially well. Carbon is everywhere. Those things together make me think probabilistically,

30:35.600 --> 30:41.120
if we found a thousand life forms, 995 of them would be carbon-based and living in water.

30:41.920 --> 30:47.280
Now the reverse question, if you found a puddle of water elsewhere and some carbon,

30:48.000 --> 30:53.680
no, just a puddle of water. Is a puddle of water a pretty damn good indication that life

30:55.600 --> 31:03.840
either exists here or has once existed here? No. So it doesn't work the other way.

31:05.280 --> 31:10.720
I think you need a living planet. You need a planet which is capable of turning over its surface. It

31:10.720 --> 31:17.360
needs to be a planet with water. It needs to be capable of bringing those electrons from inside

31:17.360 --> 31:21.920
to the outside. It needs to turn over its surface. It needs to make that water work and turn it into

31:21.920 --> 31:26.160
hydrogen. So I think you need a living planet. But once you've got the living planet, I think the

31:26.160 --> 31:32.480
rest of it is kind of thermodynamics all the way. So if you were to run Earth over a million times,

31:33.040 --> 31:41.600
up to this point, maybe beyond, to the end. Let's run it to the end. What is it? How much

31:41.600 --> 31:47.280
variety is there? You kind of spoke to this trajectory that the environment dictates

31:48.240 --> 31:56.320
like chemically, I don't know in which other way, spiritually, like dictates kind of the

31:56.320 --> 32:04.000
direction of this giant machine that seems chaotic, but it does seem to have order in the

32:04.000 --> 32:12.400
steps it's taking. How often will life, how often will bacteria emerge? How often will something

32:12.400 --> 32:17.200
like humans emerge? How much variety do you think there would be? I think at the level of bacteria,

32:17.920 --> 32:22.800
not much variety. I think we would get, that's how many times you say you want to run it a

32:22.800 --> 32:27.840
million times. I would say at least a few hundred thousand will get bacteria again.

32:29.360 --> 32:34.160
Because I think there's some level of inevitability that a wet rocky planet will give rise through

32:35.200 --> 32:41.040
the same processes to something very, I think this is not something I'd have thought a few years ago,

32:41.040 --> 32:45.200
but we're working with a PhD student of mine, Stuart Harrison. He's been thinking about the

32:45.200 --> 32:50.960
genetic code, and we've just been publishing on that. There are patterns that you can discern

32:51.040 --> 32:56.480
in the code, or he has discerned in the code, that if you think about them in terms of we start

32:56.480 --> 33:00.720
with CO2 and hydrogen, and that these are the first steps of biochemistry, you come up with a code

33:00.720 --> 33:06.000
which is very similar to the code that we see. It wouldn't surprise me any longer if we found

33:06.000 --> 33:10.400
life on Mars and it had a genetic code that was not very different to the genetic code that we have

33:10.400 --> 33:16.160
here without it just being transferred across. There's some inevitability about the whole of

33:16.160 --> 33:22.480
the beginnings of life in my view. That's really promising because if the basic chemistry is tightly

33:22.480 --> 33:30.400
linked to the genetic code, that means we can interact with other life if it exists out there.

33:30.400 --> 33:36.000
Well, that's potentially... That's really exciting if that's the case. Okay, but then bacteria...

33:36.000 --> 33:43.920
We've got bacteria. How easy is photosynthesis? Much harder, I would say.

33:44.800 --> 33:51.600
Let's actually go there. Let's go through the inventions. What is photosynthesis and why is

33:51.600 --> 33:57.680
it hard? Well, there are different forms. Basically, you're taking hydrogen and you're

33:57.680 --> 34:01.920
sticking it onto CO2 and it's powered by the sun. The question is where are you taking the hydrogen

34:01.920 --> 34:07.600
from? And in photosynthesis that we know in plants, it's coming from water. So you're using the power

34:07.600 --> 34:12.400
of the sun to split water, take out the hydrogen, stick it onto CO2, and the oxygen is a waste

34:12.400 --> 34:18.800
product and you just throw it out, throw it away. So it's the single greatest planetary pollution

34:18.800 --> 34:25.520
event in the whole history of the earth. The pollutant being oxygen. Yes. It also made possible

34:25.520 --> 34:30.480
animals. You can't have large active animals without an oxygenated atmosphere, at least not

34:31.600 --> 34:36.000
in the sense that we know on earth. So that's a really big invention in the history of earth.

34:36.000 --> 34:40.880
Huge invention, yes. And it happened once. There's a few things that happen once on earth and you're

34:40.880 --> 34:45.520
always stuck with this problem. Once it happened, did it become so good so quickly that it precluded

34:45.520 --> 34:50.480
the same thing happening ever again? Or are there other reasons? And we really have to look at each

34:50.480 --> 34:57.600
one in turn and think, why did it only happen once? In this case, it's really difficult to split

34:57.600 --> 35:02.160
water. It requires a lot of power and that power, you're effectively separating charge across a

35:02.160 --> 35:07.040
membrane and the way in which you do it, if it doesn't all rush back and kind of cause an explosion

35:07.040 --> 35:14.720
right at the site, requires really careful wiring. And that wiring, it can't be easy to get it right

35:14.720 --> 35:21.040
because the plants that we see around us, they have chloroplasts. Those chloroplasts were cyanobacteria

35:21.040 --> 35:25.760
ones. Those cyanobacteria are the only group of bacteria that can do that type of photosynthesis.

35:25.760 --> 35:31.840
So there's plenty of opportunity. So not even many bacteria. So who invented photosynthesis?

35:32.080 --> 35:34.960
The cyanobacteria or their ancestors. And there's not many...

35:36.000 --> 35:41.520
No other bacteria can do what's called oxygenic photosynthesis. Lots of other bacteria can split.

35:42.240 --> 35:45.760
You can take your hydrogen from somewhere else. You can take it from hydrogen sulfide bubbling

35:45.760 --> 35:50.800
out of a hydrothermal vent, grab your two. Hydrogens, the sulfur is the waste now.

35:52.000 --> 35:56.000
You can do it from iron. You can take electrons. So the early oceans were probably full of iron.

35:56.000 --> 36:01.680
You can take an electron from ferrous iron, so iron 2 plus and make it iron 3 plus,

36:01.680 --> 36:07.600
which now precipitates as rust. And you take a proton from the acidic early ocean,

36:07.600 --> 36:12.240
stick it there. Now you've got a hydrogen atom, stick it onto CO2. You've just done the trick.

36:12.240 --> 36:18.480
The trouble is you bury yourself in rusty iron. And with sulfur, you can bury yourself in sulfur.

36:18.480 --> 36:23.280
One of the reasons oxygenic photosynthesis is so much better is the waste product is oxygen,

36:23.280 --> 36:30.320
which just bubbles away. That seems like extremely unlikely. And it's extremely

36:30.320 --> 36:34.880
essential for the evolution of complex organisms because of all the oxygen.

36:36.080 --> 36:42.000
Yeah. And that didn't accumulate quickly either. So it's converting, what is it?

36:42.000 --> 36:49.200
It's converting energy from the sun and the resource of water into the resource needed for

36:49.200 --> 36:54.480
animals. Both resources needed for animals. We need to eat and we need to burn the food.

36:54.480 --> 37:00.480
And we're eating plants, which are getting their energy from the sun, and we're burning it with

37:00.480 --> 37:04.560
their waste product, which is the oxygen. So there's a lot of kind of circularity in that.

37:04.560 --> 37:14.880
But without an oxygenated planet, you couldn't really have predation. You can have animals,

37:14.880 --> 37:18.640
but you can't really have animals that go around and eat each other. You can't have ecosystems,

37:18.640 --> 37:24.320
as we know them. Well, let's actually step back. What about eukaryotic versus prokaryotic cells,

37:24.320 --> 37:29.840
prokaryotes? What are each of those and how big of an invention is that?

37:30.960 --> 37:34.800
I personally think that's the single biggest invention in the whole history of life.

37:34.800 --> 37:37.600
Exciting. So what are they? Can you explain?

37:37.600 --> 37:41.920
Yeah. So I mentioned bacteria and archaea. These are both prokaryotes.

37:42.960 --> 37:46.960
They're basically small cells that don't have a nucleus. If you look at them under a microscope,

37:46.960 --> 37:50.560
you don't see much going on. If you look at them under a super resolution microscope,

37:50.560 --> 37:55.440
then they're fantastically complex. In terms of their molecular machinery, they're amazing.

37:55.440 --> 38:00.320
In terms of their morphological appearance under a microscope, they're really small

38:01.440 --> 38:05.600
and really simple. The earliest life that we can physically see on the planet are

38:05.600 --> 38:10.960
stromatolites, which are made by things like cyanobacteria and their large superstructures.

38:10.960 --> 38:17.280
Effectively, biofilms plated on top of each other and you end up with quite large structures

38:17.280 --> 38:22.960
that you can see in the fossil record. But they never came out with animals.

38:22.960 --> 38:26.560
They never came out with plants. They came out with multicellular things,

38:26.560 --> 38:30.800
filamentous cyanobacteria, for example. They're just long strings of cells.

38:31.360 --> 38:37.200
But the origin of the eukaryotic cell seems to have been what's called an endosymbiosis.

38:37.360 --> 38:43.360
So one cell gets inside another cell. I think that that's transformed the energetic possibilities

38:43.360 --> 38:49.360
of life. So what we end up with is a kind of supercharged cell, which can have a much larger

38:49.920 --> 38:56.240
nucleus with many more genes, all supported. If you think about it, you could think about it as

38:56.240 --> 39:00.320
multi-bacterial power without the overhead. So you've got a cell and it's got bacteria

39:00.320 --> 39:04.960
living in it. And those bacteria are providing it with the energy currency it needs. But each

39:04.960 --> 39:11.760
bacterium has a genome of its own, which costs a fair amount of energy to express, to kind of turn

39:11.760 --> 39:17.200
over and convert into proteins and so on. What the mitochondria did, which are these

39:18.240 --> 39:23.760
power packs in our own cells, they were bacteria once and they threw away virtually all their

39:23.760 --> 39:29.120
genes. They've only got a few left. So mitochondria is, like you said, is the bacteria that got inside

39:29.120 --> 39:34.240
a cell and then throw away all this stuff it doesn't need to survive inside the cell and then

39:34.240 --> 39:40.560
kept what? So what we end up with, so it kept always a handful of genes in our own case, 37 genes.

39:41.440 --> 39:46.880
But there's a few protists, which are single cells, things that have got as many as 70 or 80

39:46.880 --> 39:52.800
genes. So it's not always the same, but it's always a small number. And you can think of it as a

39:52.800 --> 39:58.720
paired down power pack where the control unit has really been kind of paired down to almost nothing.

39:58.720 --> 40:03.760
So you're putting out the same power, but the investment in the overheads is really paired

40:03.760 --> 40:09.680
down. That means that you can support a much larger nuclear genome. So we've gone up in the

40:09.680 --> 40:13.840
number of genes, but also the amount of power you have to convert those genes into proteins.

40:14.800 --> 40:19.280
We've gone up about fourfold in the number of genes, but in terms of the size of genomes and

40:19.280 --> 40:24.000
your ability to make the building blocks, make the proteins, we've gone up a hundred thousand

40:24.000 --> 40:31.200
fold or more. So it's huge step change in the possibilities of evolution. And it's interesting

40:31.200 --> 40:36.400
then that the only, the only two occasions that complex life has arisen on earth, plants and

40:36.400 --> 40:43.120
animals, fungi, you could say are complex as well, but they don't form such complex morphology as

40:43.120 --> 40:49.120
plants and animals. Start with a single cell. They start with an oocyte and a sperm fused together

40:49.120 --> 40:54.080
to make as I got. So you start development with a single cell and all the cells in the organism

40:54.080 --> 40:59.920
have identical DNA. And you switch off in the brain, you switch off these genes and you switch on

40:59.920 --> 41:02.720
those genes and the liver, you switch off those and you switch on a different set.

41:03.920 --> 41:07.520
And the standard evolutionary explanation for that is that you've, you know, you're

41:07.520 --> 41:11.840
restricting conflict. You don't have a load of genetically different cells that are all fighting

41:11.840 --> 41:17.280
each other. And so it works. The trouble with bacteria, they form these biofilms and they're

41:17.280 --> 41:22.480
all genetically different. And effectively, they're incapable of that level of cooperation.

41:23.200 --> 41:29.760
They would get in the fight. Okay, so why is this such a difficult invention

41:31.120 --> 41:38.000
of getting this bacteria inside and becoming an engine, which the mitochondria is? Why was that?

41:38.000 --> 41:42.080
Why do you assign it such great importance? Is it great importance in terms of the difficulty

41:42.080 --> 41:46.800
of how was to achieve a great importance in terms of the impact they had on life?

41:46.880 --> 41:54.080
Both. It had a huge impact on life because if that had not happened, you can be certain

41:54.080 --> 41:58.080
that life on earth would be bacterial only. And that took a really long time to...

41:58.080 --> 42:02.640
It took two billion years. And it hasn't happened since to the best of our knowledge.

42:02.640 --> 42:07.280
So it looks as if it's genuinely difficult. And if you think about it then from just an

42:07.280 --> 42:14.240
informational perspective, you think bacteria have got, they structure their information

42:14.240 --> 42:18.960
differently. So a bacterial cell has a small genome, you might have 4,000 genes in it,

42:18.960 --> 42:24.640
but a single E. coli cell has access to about 30,000 genes. Potentially, it's got a kind of

42:24.640 --> 42:29.840
metagenome where other E. coli out there have got different gene sets and they can switch them

42:29.840 --> 42:36.160
around between themselves. And so you can generate a huge amount of variation and they've got more...

42:36.160 --> 42:42.640
An E. coli metagenome is larger than the human genome. We own 20,000 genes or something.

42:43.200 --> 42:49.920
So... And they've had 4 billion years of evolution to work out what can I do and what can't I do

42:49.920 --> 42:54.240
with this metagenome. And the answer is you're stuck. You're still bacteria.

42:54.240 --> 43:01.200
So they have explored genetic sequence space far more thoroughly than eukaryotes ever did

43:01.200 --> 43:05.840
because they've had twice as long at least and they've got much larger populations.

43:05.840 --> 43:10.640
And they never got around this problem. So why can't they? It seems as if you can't solve it

43:10.640 --> 43:18.640
with information alone. So what's the problem? The problem is structure. If cells...

43:18.640 --> 43:22.080
If the very first cells need an electrical charge on their membrane to grow

43:22.880 --> 43:27.520
and in bacteria, it's the outer membrane that surrounds the cell, which is electrically charged.

43:28.160 --> 43:32.240
You try and scale that up and you've got a fundamental design problem. You've got an

43:32.240 --> 43:37.280
engineering problem. And there are examples of it and what we see in all these cases is what's

43:37.280 --> 43:41.200
known as extreme polyploidy, which is to say they have tens of thousands of copies of their

43:41.200 --> 43:49.200
complete genome, which is energetically hugely expensive and you end up with a large bacteria with

43:50.240 --> 43:56.800
no further development. What you need is to incorporate these electrically charged power

43:56.800 --> 44:03.200
pack units inside with their control units intact. And for them not to conflict so much

44:03.200 --> 44:07.840
with the host cell that it all goes wrong. Perhaps it goes wrong more often than not.

44:07.840 --> 44:14.160
And then you change the topology of the cell. Now, you don't necessarily have any more DNA

44:14.160 --> 44:19.840
than a giant bacterium with extreme polyploidy. But what you've got is an asymmetry. You now have a

