we don't want to go there. It's not done anybody any good. In some ways, maybe it does do good.

01:05:41.040 --> 01:05:49.760
I don't want to make an argument for nuclear arms. But predation as a mechanism forces organisms to

01:05:49.760 --> 01:05:56.240
adapt change to be better to escape or to kill. If you need to eat, then you've got to eat. And

01:05:56.240 --> 01:06:03.520
a cheetah is not going to run at that speed unless it has to because the zebra is capable of escaping.

01:06:03.600 --> 01:06:10.080
So it leads to much greater feats of evolution would ever have been possible without it. And in

01:06:10.080 --> 01:06:18.320
the end, to a much more beautiful world. And so it's not all bad by any means. But the thing is,

01:06:18.320 --> 01:06:23.280
you can't have this if you don't have an oxygenated planet because it's all in the end. It's about

01:06:23.280 --> 01:06:28.320
how much energy can you extract from the food you eat. And if you don't have an oxygenated planet,

01:06:28.320 --> 01:06:34.080
you can get about 10% out, not much more than that. And if you've got an oxygenated planet,

01:06:34.080 --> 01:06:38.960
you can get about 40% out. And that means you can have instead of having one or two

01:06:38.960 --> 01:06:44.400
trophic levels, you can have five or six trophic levels. And that means things can eat things that

01:06:44.400 --> 01:06:49.520
eat other things and so on. And you've gone to a level of ecological complexity, which is completely

01:06:49.520 --> 01:06:54.240
impossible in the absence of oxygen. This reminds me of the Hunter S. Thompson quote,

01:06:54.240 --> 01:07:00.640
that for every moment of triumph, for every instance of beauty, many souls must be trampled.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:10.400
The history of life on earth, unfortunately, is that of violence, just the trillions and

01:07:10.400 --> 01:07:16.960
trillions of multi cell organisms that were murdered in the in the struggled.

01:07:16.960 --> 01:07:19.840
It's a sorry statement. But yes, it's basically true.

01:07:20.320 --> 01:07:26.240
And that somehow is a catalyst from an evolutionary perspective for creativity,

01:07:26.240 --> 01:07:30.640
for creating more and more complex organisms that are better and better at surviving.

01:07:30.640 --> 01:07:35.120
Survival of the fittest, if you just go back to that old phrase, means death the weakest.

01:07:36.240 --> 01:07:41.280
Now, what's fit, what's weak, these are terms that don't have much intrinsic meaning.

01:07:41.280 --> 01:07:44.560
But the thing is, evolution only happens because of death.

01:07:45.280 --> 01:07:51.280
One way to die is the constraints, the scarcity of the resources in the environment.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:56.640
But that seems to be not nearly as good of a mechanism for death

01:07:57.200 --> 01:08:02.240
than other creatures roam about in the environment. When I say environment,

01:08:02.240 --> 01:08:05.920
I mean like the static environment. But then there's the dynamic environment of

01:08:06.560 --> 01:08:09.760
bigger things trying to eat you and use you for your energy.

01:08:10.480 --> 01:08:14.480
It forces you to come up with a solution to your specific problem

01:08:14.960 --> 01:08:18.720
that is inventive and is new and hasn't been done before.

01:08:18.720 --> 01:08:25.920
And so it forces, I mean, literally change, literally evolution on populations,

01:08:25.920 --> 01:08:27.280
they have to become different.

01:08:27.280 --> 01:08:31.600
And it's interesting that humans have channeled that into more,

01:08:32.240 --> 01:08:35.040
I mean, I guess what humans are doing is they're inventing

01:08:35.600 --> 01:08:39.280
more productive and safe ways of doing that.

01:08:39.280 --> 01:08:42.480
You know, this whole idea of morality and all those kinds of things,

01:08:43.280 --> 01:08:49.840
I think they ultimately lead to competition versus violence.

01:08:49.840 --> 01:08:56.400
Because I think violence can have a cold, brutal, inefficient aspect to it.

01:08:56.400 --> 01:09:02.400
But if you channel that into more controlled competition in the space of ideas,

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:06.080
in the space of approaches to life, maybe you can

01:09:08.320 --> 01:09:12.160
be even more productive than evolution is, because evolution is very wasteful.

01:09:12.160 --> 01:09:16.560
Like the modern murder required to really test a good idea,

01:09:16.560 --> 01:09:21.280
genetically speaking, is just a lot. Many, many, many generations.

01:09:21.280 --> 01:09:25.840
Morally, we cannot base society on the way that evolution works.

01:09:25.840 --> 01:09:27.200
That's an invention, right?

01:09:27.200 --> 01:09:30.320
But actually, in some respects, we do, which is to say,

01:09:30.320 --> 01:09:32.880
this is how science works. We have competing hypotheses

01:09:32.880 --> 01:09:35.280
that have to get better, otherwise they die.

01:09:35.280 --> 01:09:38.480
It's the way that society works. In ancient Greece,

01:09:38.480 --> 01:09:42.480
we had the Athens and Sparta and city-states,

01:09:42.480 --> 01:09:45.280
and then we had the Renaissance and nation-states.

01:09:45.280 --> 01:09:47.840
And universities compete with each other.

01:09:47.840 --> 01:09:48.320
Yes.

01:09:48.320 --> 01:09:51.680
Tremendous amount of companies competing with each other all the time.

01:09:51.680 --> 01:09:53.440
It drives innovation.

01:09:54.960 --> 01:09:59.040
And if we want to do it without all the death that we see in nature,

01:09:59.040 --> 01:10:03.760
then we have to have some kind of societal level control that says,

01:10:03.760 --> 01:10:07.200
well, there's some limits, guys, and these are what the limits are going to be.

01:10:07.200 --> 01:10:10.880
And society as a whole has to say, right, we want to limit the amount of death here,

01:10:10.880 --> 01:10:12.720
so you can't do this and you can't do that.

01:10:12.720 --> 01:10:14.960
And who makes up these rules and how do we know?

01:10:14.960 --> 01:10:19.440
It's a tough thing, but it's basically trying to find a moral basis

01:10:19.440 --> 01:10:22.960
for avoiding the death of evolution and natural selection

01:10:22.960 --> 01:10:26.720
and keeping the innovation and the richness of it.

01:10:27.280 --> 01:10:31.760
And I forgot who said it, but that murder is illegal,

01:10:31.760 --> 01:10:34.320
probably curve out of it, murder is illegal,

01:10:34.320 --> 01:10:38.160
except when it's done to the sound of trumpets and at a large scale.

01:10:38.160 --> 01:10:40.160
So we still have wars.

01:10:41.680 --> 01:10:46.400
But we are struggling with this idea that murder is a bad thing.

01:10:47.280 --> 01:10:52.400
It's so interesting how we're channeling the best of the evolutionary imperative

01:10:53.280 --> 01:10:57.600
and trying to get rid of the stuff that's not productive.

01:10:58.400 --> 01:11:00.560
So trying to almost accelerate evolution,

01:11:00.560 --> 01:11:07.280
the same kind of thing that makes evolution creative, we're trying to use that.

01:11:07.280 --> 01:11:08.560
I think we naturally do it.

01:11:08.560 --> 01:11:10.480
I mean, I don't think we can help ourselves do it.

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:16.560
Capitalism as a form is basically about competition and differential rewards.

01:11:17.200 --> 01:11:25.120
But society, and I keep using this word moral obligation,

01:11:26.480 --> 01:11:29.760
we cannot operate as a society if we go that way.

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:35.120
It's interesting that we've had problems achieving balance.

01:11:35.120 --> 01:11:38.640
So for example, in the financial crash in 2009,

01:11:39.280 --> 01:11:41.200
do you let banks go to the wall or not?

01:11:41.200 --> 01:11:42.880
This is kind of question.

01:11:42.880 --> 01:11:44.960
In evolution, certainly you let them go to the wall,

01:11:44.960 --> 01:11:49.280
and in that sense, you don't need the regulation because they just die.

01:11:51.360 --> 01:11:56.240
Whereas if we as a society think about what's required for society as a whole,

01:11:56.240 --> 01:11:58.400
then you don't necessarily let them go to the wall.

01:11:59.360 --> 01:12:05.360
In which case, you then have to impose some kind of regulation that the bankers themselves will

01:12:05.360 --> 01:12:07.040
in an evolutionary manner exploit.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:12.720
Yeah, we've been struggling with this kind of idea of capitalism,

01:12:13.360 --> 01:12:19.600
the cold brutality of capitalism that seems to create so much beautiful things in this world,

01:12:20.240 --> 01:12:26.480
and then the ideals of communism that seem to create so much brutal destruction in history.

01:12:26.480 --> 01:12:30.400
We struggle with ideas of, well, maybe we didn't do it right.

01:12:30.400 --> 01:12:31.600
How can we do things better?

01:12:31.600 --> 01:12:35.840
And then the ideas are the things we're playing with as opposed to people.

01:12:35.920 --> 01:12:38.960
If a PhD student has a bad idea, we don't shoot the PhD student.

01:12:38.960 --> 01:12:41.920
We just criticize their idea and hope they improve.

01:12:41.920 --> 01:12:43.120
You have a very humane lamp.

01:12:43.920 --> 01:12:45.520
Yeah, I don't know how you guys do it.

01:12:45.520 --> 01:12:49.280
You know, the way I run things, it's always life and death.

01:12:49.280 --> 01:12:54.560
Okay, so it is interesting about humans that there is an inner sense of morality,

01:12:55.600 --> 01:13:02.320
which begs the question of how did homo sapiens evolve?

01:13:02.320 --> 01:13:08.880
If we think about the invention of early invention of sex and early invention of predation,

01:13:10.560 --> 01:13:14.240
what was the thing invented to make humans?

01:13:15.360 --> 01:13:16.560
What would you say?

01:13:17.040 --> 01:13:19.120
I mean, I suppose a couple of things I'd say.

01:13:19.120 --> 01:13:24.080
Number one is you don't have to wind the clock back very far, five, six million years or so,

01:13:24.080 --> 01:13:26.560
and let it run forwards again.

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:30.240
And the chances of humans, as we know them, is not necessarily that high.

01:13:30.880 --> 01:13:35.200
Now, you know, imagine, as an alien, you find planet Earth and it's got everything

01:13:35.200 --> 01:13:39.280
apart from humans on it, it's an amazing, wonderful, marvelous planet,

01:13:39.280 --> 01:13:43.520
but nothing that we would recognize as extremely intelligent life,

01:13:43.520 --> 01:13:45.680
kind of space-faring civilization.

01:13:45.680 --> 01:13:49.600
So when we think about aliens, we're kind of after something like ourselves,

01:13:49.600 --> 01:13:51.680
or after a space-faring civilization.

01:13:51.680 --> 01:13:55.760
We're not after zebras and giraffes and lions and things.

01:13:55.760 --> 01:13:56.880
Amazing though they are.

01:13:57.680 --> 01:14:05.520
But the additional kind of evolutionary steps to go from large complex mammals, monkeys, let's say,

01:14:07.360 --> 01:14:12.960
to humans doesn't strike me as that longer a distance.

01:14:12.960 --> 01:14:14.400
It's all about the brain.

01:14:14.400 --> 01:14:17.040
And where's the brain and morality coming from?

01:14:17.040 --> 01:14:22.320
It seems to me to be all about groups, human groups and interactions between groups.

01:14:22.320 --> 01:14:23.760
The collective intelligence of it.

01:14:24.400 --> 01:14:26.640
Yes, the interactions really.

01:14:26.640 --> 01:14:31.920
And there's a guy at UCL called Mark Thomas who's done a lot of really beautiful work,

01:14:31.920 --> 01:14:33.440
I think, on this kind of question.

01:14:33.440 --> 01:14:37.040
So I talk to him every now and then, so my view is influenced by him.

01:14:38.880 --> 01:14:42.480
But a lot seems to depend on population density.

01:14:43.440 --> 01:14:46.560
The more interactions you have going on between different groups,

01:14:46.560 --> 01:14:50.320
the more transfer of information, if you like, between groups,

01:14:50.320 --> 01:14:53.520
so people moving from one group to another group,

01:14:53.520 --> 01:14:55.840
almost like lateral gene transfer in bacteria.

01:14:57.200 --> 01:15:01.040
The more expertise you're able to develop and maintain,

01:15:01.040 --> 01:15:04.400
the more culturally complex your society can become.

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:09.200
And groups that have become detached, like on Easter Island, for example,

01:15:09.200 --> 01:15:13.520
very often degenerate in terms of the complexity of their civilization.

01:15:13.520 --> 01:15:16.080
Is that true for complex organisms in general?

01:15:16.080 --> 01:15:18.560
Population density is often productive.

01:15:19.200 --> 01:15:19.760
Really matters.

01:15:19.760 --> 01:15:26.000
But in human terms, I don't know what the actual factors were

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:28.560
that were driving a large brain.

01:15:28.560 --> 01:15:30.720
But you can talk about fire.

01:15:30.720 --> 01:15:32.880
You can talk about tool use.

01:15:32.880 --> 01:15:34.080
You can talk about language.

01:15:34.080 --> 01:15:36.720
And none of them seem to correlate especially well

01:15:36.720 --> 01:15:42.800
with the actual known trajectory of human evolution in terms of cave art and these kind of things.

01:15:42.800 --> 01:15:47.520
That seems to work much better just with population density

01:15:47.520 --> 01:15:50.480
and a number of interactions between different groups.

01:15:51.120 --> 01:15:55.760
All of which is really about human interactions.

01:15:55.760 --> 01:15:58.560
Human-human interactions and the complexity of those.

01:15:58.560 --> 01:16:04.160
But population density is the thing that increases the number of interactions.

01:16:04.160 --> 01:16:06.320
But then there must have been inventions

01:16:09.440 --> 01:16:14.560
forced by that number of interactions that actually led to humans.

01:16:14.560 --> 01:16:21.360
So like Richard Rangham talks about that it's basically the beta males had to beat up the alpha

01:16:21.360 --> 01:16:25.760
male. So that's what collaboration looks like is they, when you're living together,

01:16:25.760 --> 01:16:34.480
they don't like, our early ancestors don't like the dictatorial aspect of a single individual

01:16:34.480 --> 01:16:35.440
at the top of a tribe.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:42.720
So they learn to collaborate how to basically create a democracy of sorts,

01:16:42.720 --> 01:16:47.200
a democracy that prevents, minimizes or lessens the amount of violence,

01:16:47.280 --> 01:16:54.960
which essentially gives strength to the tribe and make the war between tribes versus the dictator.

01:16:54.960 --> 01:17:00.320
I mean, I think one of the most wonderful things about humans is where all of those things.

01:17:00.320 --> 01:17:05.280
I mean, we are deeply social as a species and we're also deeply selfish.

01:17:05.280 --> 01:17:08.400
And it seems to me the conflict between capitalism and communism,

01:17:08.400 --> 01:17:11.120
it's really just two aspects of human nature, both of which are.

01:17:11.120 --> 01:17:11.760
Yeah, both.

01:17:11.760 --> 01:17:16.080
We have both and we have a constant kind of vying between the two sides.

01:17:16.080 --> 01:17:21.120
We really do care about other people beyond our families, beyond our immediate people.

01:17:21.120 --> 01:17:23.920
We care about society and the society that we live in.

01:17:24.480 --> 01:17:28.480
And you could say that's a drawing towards socialism or communism.

01:17:28.480 --> 01:17:30.640
On the other side, we really do care about ourselves.

01:17:30.640 --> 01:17:34.640
We really do care about our families about working for something that we gain from.

01:17:34.640 --> 01:17:35.920
And that's the capitalist side of it.

01:17:35.920 --> 01:17:38.000
They're both really deeply ingrained in human nature.

01:17:38.800 --> 01:17:43.200
In terms of violence and interactions between groups,

01:17:43.280 --> 01:17:47.120
yes, all this dynamic of if you're interacting between groups,

01:17:47.120 --> 01:17:50.240
you can be certain that they're going to be burning each other

01:17:50.240 --> 01:17:53.360
and all kinds of physical, violent interactions as well,

01:17:53.360 --> 01:17:57.760
which will drive the kind of cleverness of how do you resist this?

01:17:57.760 --> 01:17:58.800
Let's build a tower.

01:17:58.800 --> 01:18:02.560
Let's see, what are we going to do to prevent being overrun

01:18:02.560 --> 01:18:04.880
by those marauding gangs from over there?

01:18:06.400 --> 01:18:10.640
And you look outside humans and you look at chimps and bonobos and so on.

01:18:10.720 --> 01:18:13.280
And they're very, very different structures to society.

01:18:13.280 --> 01:18:17.280
Chimps tend to have an aggressive alpha male type structure and bonobos.

01:18:19.440 --> 01:18:22.800
There's basically a female society where the males are predominantly excluded

01:18:22.800 --> 01:18:24.640
and only brought in at the behest of the female.

01:18:25.600 --> 01:18:29.200
We have a lot in common with both of those groups.

01:18:29.200 --> 01:18:31.200
And there's again tension there.

01:18:31.200 --> 01:18:34.800
And probably chimps more violent, so bonobos probably more sex.

01:18:35.360 --> 01:18:36.560
That's another tension.

01:18:37.440 --> 01:18:42.160
How serious do we want to be?

01:18:42.160 --> 01:18:43.200
How much fun do we want to be?

01:18:44.080 --> 01:18:47.840
Asking for a friend again, what do you think happened to Neanderthals?

01:18:47.840 --> 01:18:52.880
What did we cheeky humans do to the Neanderthals, homo sapiens?

01:18:52.880 --> 01:18:54.080
Do you think we murdered them?

01:18:55.600 --> 01:18:56.640
How do we murder them?

01:18:56.640 --> 01:18:57.920
How do we out-compete them?

01:18:59.200 --> 01:19:01.200
Or do we out-mate them?

01:19:01.200 --> 01:19:02.000
I don't know.

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:05.280
I mean, I think there's unequivocal evidence that we mated with them.

01:19:05.920 --> 01:19:07.680
We always try to mate with everything.

01:19:07.680 --> 01:19:08.480
Yes, pretty much.

01:19:09.360 --> 01:19:10.240
There's some interesting.

01:19:10.240 --> 01:19:13.280
The first sequences that came along were in mitochondrial DNA.

01:19:14.400 --> 01:19:16.960
And that was back to about 2002 or thereabouts.

01:19:18.480 --> 01:19:22.080
What was found was that Neanderthal mitochondrial DNA was very different

01:19:22.080 --> 01:19:23.280
to human mitochondria.

01:19:23.280 --> 01:19:23.840
Oh, that's so interesting.

01:19:23.840 --> 01:19:24.960
You could do a clock on it.

01:19:24.960 --> 01:19:28.400
And they said the divergent state was about 600,000 years ago

01:19:28.400 --> 01:19:30.160
or something like that, so not so long ago.

01:19:31.360 --> 01:19:33.920
And then the first full genomes were sequenced,

01:19:33.920 --> 01:19:35.200
maybe 10 years after that.

01:19:36.000 --> 01:19:39.520
And they showed plenty of signs of mating between.

01:19:39.520 --> 01:19:42.240
So the mitochondrial DNA effectively says no mating.

01:19:43.040 --> 01:19:46.880
And the nuclear genes say, yeah, lots of mating.

01:19:47.760 --> 01:19:48.320
But we don't know.

01:19:48.320 --> 01:19:49.120
Is that possible?

01:19:49.120 --> 01:19:53.760
So can you explain the difference between mitochondrial DNA and nucleus?

01:19:53.760 --> 01:19:55.520
I've talked before about the mitochondria,

01:19:55.520 --> 01:19:57.360
which are the power packs in cells.

01:19:57.360 --> 01:20:00.800
These are the paired down control units is their DNA.

01:20:01.360 --> 01:20:03.760
So it's passed on by the mother only.

01:20:04.880 --> 01:20:10.480
And in the egg cell, we might have half a million copies of mitochondrial DNA.

01:20:10.480 --> 01:20:12.320
There's only 37 genes left.

01:20:13.360 --> 01:20:17.040
And they do basically the control unit of energy production.

01:20:17.040 --> 01:20:18.400
That's what it's doing.

01:20:18.400 --> 01:20:21.520
It's a basic old school machine that does.

01:20:21.520 --> 01:20:24.800
And it's got genes that were considered to be effectively trivial

01:20:24.800 --> 01:20:28.640
because they did a very narrowly defined job.

01:20:28.640 --> 01:20:31.920
But they're not trivial in the sense that that narrowly defined job is about

01:20:32.640 --> 01:20:34.320
everything that is being alive.

01:20:36.960 --> 01:20:38.080
So they're much easier to sequence.

01:20:38.080 --> 01:20:39.680
You've got many more copies of these things.

01:20:39.680 --> 01:20:41.120
And you can sequence them very quickly.

01:20:42.000 --> 01:20:46.240
But the problem is because they go down only the maternal line from mother to daughter,

01:20:46.240 --> 01:20:49.520
your mitochondrial DNA and mine is going nowhere.

01:20:49.520 --> 01:20:53.680
Doesn't matter any kids we have, they get their mother's mitochondrial DNA.

01:20:54.800 --> 01:20:58.800
Except in very, very rare and strange circumstances.

01:20:59.760 --> 01:21:02.240
And so it tells a different story.

01:21:02.240 --> 01:21:05.760
And it's not a story which is easy to reconcile always.

01:21:06.800 --> 01:21:11.360
And what it seems to suggest to my mind at least is that there was one way

01:21:12.480 --> 01:21:17.440
traffic of genes probably going from humans into Neanderthals rather than the other way around.

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:19.760
Why did the Neanderthals disappear?

01:21:19.760 --> 01:21:20.720
I don't know.

01:21:20.720 --> 01:21:26.400
I mean, I suspect that they were probably less violent, less clever,

01:21:27.360 --> 01:21:31.520
less populace, less willing to fight.

01:21:31.520 --> 01:21:32.400
I don't know.

01:21:32.400 --> 01:21:35.760
I mean, I think I already drove them to extinction at the margins of Europe.

01:21:37.120 --> 01:21:40.880
And it's interesting how much if we ran earth over and over again,

01:21:41.440 --> 01:21:47.360
how many of these branches of intelligent beings that have figured out some kind of

01:21:49.600 --> 01:21:53.680
how to leverage collective intelligence, which ones of them emerge,

01:21:53.680 --> 01:21:55.600
which one of them succeed?

01:21:55.600 --> 01:21:57.040
Is it the more violent ones?

01:21:57.760 --> 01:22:01.040
Is it the more isolated ones?

01:22:01.040 --> 01:22:03.840
You know, like what dynamics result to more productivity?

01:22:03.840 --> 01:22:05.440
And I suppose we'll never know.

01:22:06.320 --> 01:22:10.640
The more complex the organism, the harder it is to run the experiment in the lab.

01:22:10.640 --> 01:22:10.960
Yes.

01:22:12.080 --> 01:22:14.240
And in some respects, maybe it's best if we don't know.

